content.problemStatement:
In the previous demo, the application failed to start because Spring found two payment services and didn’t know which one to inject. \
Now let’s learn how to guide Spring.

---

**Solution 1: Using `@Primary`**
- When multiple payment service classes exist, we tell Spring which one to use by default.
- Spring will automatically use this default service unless we explicitly ask for another one.

**Step 1**: Mark One Payment Service(`UPIPaymentService.java`) as **`Primary`** \
Open `UPIPaymentService.java` and add this code in that
```java
package com.example.demo.service;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Primary;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service
@Primary
public class UPIPaymentService implements PaymentServiceInterface {

    @Override
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Payment done using UPI");
    }
}
```
`CreditCardPaymentService` remains unchanged:

---

**What Happens Now?**
- Spring finds two `PaymentService` beans(objects)
- Sees one marked as `@Primary`
- Injects `UPIPaymentService`

**Application starts successfully**

---

**Solution 2: Using `@Qualifier`** \
Instead of a default, explicitly tell Spring which bean you want.



**Step 1: Name the Payment Service Bean(Object)** \
When multiple classes implement the same interface, Spring needs a name to identify each one.
```java
package com.example.demo.service;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;

@Service("UPIPaymentService")
public class UPIPaymentService implements PaymentServiceInterface {

    @Override
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Payment done using UPI");
    }
}
```

- `@Service("UPIPaymentService")` tells Spring: \
**“Register this class with the bean name UPIPaymentService”**




**Step 2**: Use `@Qualifier` in `OrderService`
```java
package com.example.demo.service;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Qualifier;

@Service
public class OrderService {

    private final PaymentServiceInterface paymentService;

    public OrderService( @Qualifier("UPIPaymentService") PaymentServiceInterface paymentService) 
    {
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }

    public void placeOrder() {
        paymentService.pay();
        System.out.println("Order placed");
    }
}
```

- `@Qualifier("UPIPaymentService")` tells Spring:
**“Inject the bean whose name is UPIPaymentService”** 

---

**What Happens Now?**
- Spring sees multiple implementations
- Reads the qualifier name
- Injects `UPIPaymentService` only

**Application runs successfully**

---


**Expected Output After Applying both solutions:**
```sss
Payment done using UPI
Order placed
```

